<DOC><DOCNO> AP881015-0029 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-15-88 0259EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Burma     10-15 0324</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Burma,0333</SECOND><HEAD>Four More Killed, Burma's Elections to Be Held No Sooner Than 1989</HEAD><BYLINE>By SEIN WIN</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Soldiers killed four more people in themilitary government's crackdown on unrest, state-run radioreported, and officials said elections will not be held before nextyear.   The latest killings, reported Friday, lifted to more than 450the official count of people slain by troops since a Sept. 18military coup.   The radio said two of the dead were looters, and the others wereshot when they ran away after troops stopped them for violatingcurfew.   The killings follow pro-democracy protests that began after NeWin, who seized power in a military coup 26 years ago, stepped downin July. Two more governments fell during widespread protests, buthardline Gen. Saw Maung seized power Sept. 18 and ordered troops toshoot if necessary.   He also promised general elections within about three months.   ``All arrangements are expected to be ready by early next year,and the date for holding of elections will be decided afterconsultation with political parties,'' the chairman of thegovernment's election commission, Ba Htay, told representatives ofregistered parties on Friday in a statement carried by Rangoonradio.   Eighteen parties have officially registered, but none has saidif it will participate in elections run by the government.   The National Unity Party, which under a different name wasBurma's sole political for 26 years, is expected to have thesupport of the government and military.   The chairman said registered parties may open branchesthroughout the country after consultation with ``law and orderrestoration councils,'' which were set up by Saw Maung. The partieswill be allowed to carry out organizational work on their ownpremises, although a ban on public meetings of more than fivepeople is still in force.   The commission head said, ``The commission will try its best tohold a free and fair general election.''</TEXT></DOC>